{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox artist | name = Gladys Anderson | image = | caption = | birth_name = Gladys Louise Anderson | birth_date = 19th century | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | movement = | spouse = Andy J Anderson | awards = | patrons = | field = [[Painting]] | training = | works = The Passing Stream }}
'''Gladys Louise Anderson''' was a New Zealand artist, born in the 19th century.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/artist/1466/gladys-anderson|title=Gladys Anderson|work=Auckland Art Gallery|access-date=24 September 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findnzartists.org.nz/artist/261/|title=Anderson, Gladys L.|last=|first=|date=|website=findnzartists.org.nz|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref>
== Career == Gladys Anderson was known for [[Woodcut|woodcuts]] and [[Linocut|linocuts]], works include ''The Passing Stream'' (c. 1929).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aucklandartgallery.com/explore-art-and-ideas/artwork/695/the-passing-stream|title=The Passing Stream|work=Auckland Art Gallery|access-date=24 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>
Anderson was exhibited with [[The Group (New Zealand art)|The Group]], an informal art association from [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, formed to provide a freer alternative to the [[Canterbury Society of Arts]]. She contributed works to exhibitions in: 1933<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/about/library/the-group/-1933|title=The Group 1933|last=|first=|date=|website=christchurchartgallery.org.nz|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref> and 1934.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://christchurchartgallery.org.nz/about/library/the-group/-1934|title=The Group 1934|last=|first=|date=|website=christchurchartgallery.org.nz|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref> She also exhibited with the Canterbury Society of Arts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findnzartists.org.nz/artists/exhibition/2/|title=Artists exhibited with Canterbury Society of Arts|last=|first=|date=|website=findnzartists.org.nz|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref> New Zealand Academy of Fine Arts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findnzartists.org.nz/artists/exhibition/4/|title=Artists exhibited with New Zealand Academy of Fine Arts|last=|first=|date=|website=findnzartists.org.nz|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref> and Otago Art Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://findnzartists.org.nz/artists/exhibition/7/|title=Artists exhibited with Otago Art Society|last=|first=|date=|website=findnzartists.org.nz|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref>
=== New Zealand Motor Caravan Association === Gladys Anderson and her husband Andy J Anderson had a passion for motor caravans, purchasing their first vintage passenger bus in 1955. Her husband formed the NZ Motor Caravan Association<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nzmca.org.nz/how-it-all-began/|title=NZMCA : How It All Began|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nzmca.org.nz|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=24 September 2017}}</ref> and Gladys is the author of ''The History of the First 21 Years of the N.Z.M.C.A. Inc., 1956–1977'', published in 1977 by the New Zealand Motor Caravan Association.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/The_History_of_the_First_21_Years_of_the.html?id=VUC3MQAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=The History of the First 21 Years of the N.Z.M.C.A. Inc., 1956–1977|last=Anderson|first=Gladys|date=1977|publisher=N.Z. Motor-Caravan Assn|language=en}}</ref>
