'''Shērōē''' (also spelled '''Shīrūya''', {{lang|fa|شیرویه}} in [[New Persian]]), better known by his dynastic name of '''Kavadh II''' ([[Middle Persian]]: kwʾt' ''Kawād''; New {{lang-fa|قباد}} ''Qobād'' or ''Qabād''), was king of the [[Sasanian Empire]] briefly in 628. He was the son of [[Khosrau II | Khosrow II]]. He became king after orchestrating a [[coup d'état]] against his father.

== Biography ==
Kavadh II was the son of [[Khosrau II | Khosrow II]], the king of the Sasanian Empire, and [[Maria (daughter of Maurice)|Maria]], daughter of [[Maurice (emperor)|Maurice]], the emperor of the [[Byzantine Empire]]. Kavadh was later imprisoned by his father, who wanted to ensure the succession of his favorite son [[Mardanshah (Sasanian prince)|Mardanshah]], the son of his favorite wife, [[Shirin]].

His father's reputation had been ruined during the last phase of the [[Byzantine–Sasanian War of 602–628]]. In 627, the Sasanian general [[Rhahzadh]] was slain and [[Dastagird|Dastgerd]], the king's favorite residence, had been sacked into oblivion by Byzantine emperor [[Heraclius]], who was advancing towards the nearby Sasanian capital of [[Ctesiphon]] (both in present Iraq). In 628, Kavadh was released by the feudal families of the Sasanian Empire, which included the [[Ispahbudhan]] ''[[spahbed]]'' (army chief) [[Farrukh Hormizd]] and his two sons [[Rostam Farrokhzad]] and [[Farrukhzad]], [[Shahrbaraz]] of the [[House of Mihran]], the Armenian faction represented by [[Varaztirots II Bagratuni]] and finally the [[Kanarang]].<ref>Pourshariati (2008), p. 173</ref>

On 25 February, Kavadh, along with [[Aspad Gushnasp]], captured Ctesiphon and imprisoned Khosrow II. Kavadh II then proclaimed himself as king of the Sasanian Empire and ordered the execution of all his brothers and half-brothers, which included his main rival Mardanshah, the favorite son of Khosrow II. Three days later he ordered [[Mihr Hormozd]] to execute his father. However, after the regicide of his father, Kavadh had Mihr Hormozd killed.{{sfn|Al-Tabari|1999|pp=389}}

With the agreement of the Persian nobles, Kavadh then made peace with the victorious emperor Heraclius, which awarded the Byzantines to (re)gain all their lost territories, their captured soldiers, a [[war indemnity]], along with the [[True Cross]] and other relics that were lost in Jerusalem in 614.<ref name = "Oman212">{{Harvnb|Oman|1893|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=N6A-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA212 212]}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Kaegi|2003|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=tlNlFZ_7UhoC&pg=PA178 178], [https://books.google.com/books?id=tlNlFZ_7UhoC&pg=PA189 189–190]}}</ref>

Kavadh also appointed Armenian nobleman [[Varaztirots II Bagratuni]] as [[Marzban]] (margrave and military viceroy) of [[Persian Armenia]], and appointed [[Ishoyahb II]] (628–645) as the new [[Catholicos]] (Eastern Patriarch) of the Nestorian [[Church of the East]] (at Seleucia-Ctesiphon).<ref>Nahal Tajadod, ''Les Porteurs de Lumière'', Plon, Paris, 1993, 323–324.</ref>

Kavadh II later died from plague after a few months' reign on 6 September 628. He was succeeded by his eight-year-old son [[Ardashir III]], for whom he decreed Emperor Heraclius act as regent. These decisions along with his Christian faith (from his mother) led the [[Zoroastrian]] priesthood to eliminate him and his young heir not long after.

==Marriage==
A passage of the [[Bishopric of Edessa|Chronicle of Edessa]] identifies "Anzoy the Roman" as the wife of Kavadh II and mother of Ardashir III. She was probably a Christian princess from the Byzantine Empire.<ref name="PLRE">Martindale, Jones & Morris (1992), p. 94</ref>

==In popular culture==
{{Main article|Siroe}}
Siroe is the subject of [[opera]]s by a number of composers on a libretto by [[Metastasio]], including [[Pasquale Errichelli]], [[Johann Adolph Hasse]], [[Leonardo Vinci]], [[Antonio Vivaldi]] and [[George Frideric Handel]]. He is also identified as Solomon of Persia by the [[Alians]].

