{{Infobox person | name = Peter Aaby | image = | birth_date = {{birth date|1944|11|6|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Lund]], [[Sweden]] | citizenship = [[Denmark|Danish]] | module = {{Infobox scientist | embed = yes | field = [[Health]], [[epidemiology]] | work_institutions = [[Bandim Health Project]] | alma_mater = [[University of Copenhagen]] | known_for = [[Non-specific effect of vaccines|Non-specific effects of vaccines]] | awards = Novo Nordisk Prize (2000) }} }}
'''Peter Aaby''' ([[Danes|Danish]], born 1944 in [[Lund]], [[Sweden]]) is trained as an [[anthropologist]] but also holds a [[doctoral degree]] in [[medicine]].<ref name="Winkel, 2011">{{cite book|last1=Winkel|first1=Klaus|title=Danskere i tropisk Afrika : fra slavehandler til bistandsarbejder|date=2011|publisher=Klim|location=Århus|isbn=8779559271|edition=1. udgave.}}</ref> In 1978, Peter Aaby established the [[Bandim Health Project]], a Health and Demographic Surveillance System site in [[Guinea-Bissau]] in [[West Africa]], which he has run ever since.<ref name="Bandim, 2015">{{cite web|title=Background|url=http://bandim.org/about-bhp/background.aspx|website=Bandim Health Project|publisher=SSI|accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref> In 2000, Peter Aaby was awarded the [[Novo Nordisk]] Prize, the most important Danish award within [[Outline of health sciences|health research]].
Aaby is credited for the discovery of [[non-specific effect of vaccines|non-specific effects of vaccines]] – i.e. effects of [[vaccine]]s, which go beyond the specific protective effects against the targeted diseases.<ref name="Prentice, 2009">{{cite journal|last1=Prentice|first1=AM|last2=Savy|first2=M|last3=Darboe|first3=MK|last4=Moore|first4=SE|title=Commentary: Challenging public health orthodoxies--prophesy or heresy?|journal=International Journal of Epidemiology|date=April 2009|volume=38|issue=2|pages=591–3|pmid=19174540|url=http://ije.oxfordjournals.org/content/38/2/591.short|doi=10.1093/ije/dyn363|pmc=2663722}}</ref> The theory of non-specific effects of vaccines was established in 1991 and later documented in several trials on [[measles vaccine]], [[BCG vaccine|BCG]], [[oral polio vaccine]], [[DTP vaccine]] and [[smallpox vaccine]].<ref name="Benn, 2013">{{cite journal|last1=Benn|first1=CS|last2=Netea|first2=MG|last3=Selin|first3=LK|last4=Aaby|first4=P|title=A small jab - a big effect: nonspecific immunomodulation by vaccines.|journal=Trends in Immunology|date=September 2013|volume=34|issue=9|pages=431–9|pmid=23680130|doi=10.1016/j.it.2013.04.004}}</ref> As a consequence of Aaby’s work on non-specific effects of vaccines it has been recommended the WHO [[vaccination program]] in [[low income countries]] should be changed.<ref name="Shann, 2013">{{cite journal|last1=Shann|first1=F|title=Nonspecific effects of vaccines and the reduction of mortality in children.|journal=Clinical Therapeutics|date=February 2013|volume=35|issue=2|pages=109–14|pmid=23375475|doi=10.1016/j.clinthera.2013.01.007}}</ref> [[WHO]] recently reviewed the evidence for non-specific effects of BCG vaccine, measles vaccine and DTP vaccine, and concluded that it would "keep a watch on the evidence of nonspecific effects of vaccination".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Meeting of Global Advisory Committee on Vaccine Safety, 18-19 June 2008|pmid=18689006 | volume=83 |issue=32 | date=Aug 2008|journal=Wkly Epidemiol Rec|pages=287–92}}</ref>
